body:
Currying was mentioned here a couple times but I could find any clear explanation how to "style" it properly.

Consider this code for example

```js
let fn = a => b => c => {
  // there will be some complex logic
  console.log(a, b, c);
  return a + b + c;
}
```

ESLint throws the error **arrow-parens** `Expected parentheses around arrow function argument having a body with curly braces` and forces me to style the code this way (which looks a bit "off" and inconsistent to me)

```js
let fn = a => b => (c) => {
  // there will be some complex logic
  console.log(a, b, c);
  return a + b + c;
}
```

If I try to achieve consistency by using the following styling, I will get another error **arrow-parens** `Unexpected parentheses around single function argument having a body with no curly braces`

```js
let fn = (a) => (b) => (c) => {
  // there will be some complex logic
  console.log(a, b, c);
  return a + b + c;
}
```
Is there any "convention" on how to style curryed functions?

```javascript
{
  'x.y'() {}
}
```

Above code would be invalid, have to change to 
```javascript
{
  'x.y': function () {}
}
```

Seriosly I have no idea why we have to do this.
  
The guide said:
https://github.com/airbnb/javascript/blob/2ba36de952fcb6a931471980f4fbbdc4df468baa/README.md#L195-L215

When we need to use `avoidQuotes`?
I read the change history of the eslint config, found following:
https://github.com/airbnb/javascript/commit/10f4dd88aaab6a8456373a3a0c5fc00ada3c4172

What does the "consise form" mean in the commit message?
